<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>beat the clock • beat the time</xh5><p> <i>beat the clock—</i>complete the task before a stated time: Any job is much harder if you are trying to <u>beat the clock</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>flog the clock</b>—(Nautical) move the hands of the clock forward (to quit one’s job before the due time): I got suspicious that the <u>clock was being flogged</u> in the interest of making the time of those in the mate’s watch shorter.</p><p><i>beat the time—</i>1. <i>(Music)</i> mark or follow the rhythm with the feet, a baton, etc. <i>(also: beat time): </i>The captain joined in with a long raucous song, <u>beating time</u> on the tea tray. 2. <i>(Sport)</i> improve on smb.’s achievement: He’s hoping to ride two hundred miles in less than eight and a half hours, <u>beating the time</u> set by an eccentric Yorkshireman in 1831.</p> </entry>
